The  Cube  class represents cubes that are used in a board game. There are three types of cubes.

Number cubes, whose faces are labeled with the numbers 1 through 6

Letter cubes, whose faces are labeled with the letters A through F

Color cubes, whose faces are labeled with the colors red, orange, yellow, green, blue, and purple

A partial  Cube  class definition is shown.
 public class Cube
{
 /** 
 * Constructs a Cube object. If the parameter is
 * equal to "number", the cube will be a number
 * cube. If the parameter is equal to "letter", the 
 * cube will be a letter cube. If the parameter is
 * equal to "color", the cube will be a color cube. 
 * Precondition: cubeType is equal to "number",
 * "letter", or "color".
 */
 public Cube(String cubeType)
 { /* implementation not shown */ }

/**
 * Returns "1", "2", "3", "4", "5", or "6" if
 * the cube is a number cube, returns "A", "B",
 * "C", "D", "E", or "F" if the cube is a
 * letter cube, and returns "red", "orange",
 * "yellow", "green", "blue", or "purple" if 
 * the cube is a color cube 
 */
 public String roll()
 { /* implementation not shown */ }

/* There may be instance variables, constructors,
 and methods that are not shown. */
}

You will write a class  CubePair  to represent two  Cube  objects that are used in a game. The  CubePair  class should have a one-parameter constructor, a two-parameter constructor, and a  rollCubes  method.

